21/* There are many algorithms for performing strength reduction on
22 loops. This is not one of them. IVOPTS handles strength reduction
23 of induction variables just fine. This pass is intended to pick
24 up the crumbs it leaves behind, by considering opportunities for
25 strength reduction along dominator paths.
26
27 Strength reduction addresses explicit multiplies, and certain
28 multiplies implicit in addressing expressions. It would also be
29 possible to apply strength reduction to divisions and modulos,
30 but such opportunities are relatively uncommon.
31
32 Strength reduction is also currently restricted to integer operations.
33 If desired, it could be extended to floating-point operations under
34 control of something like -funsafe-math-optimizations. */
35

61/* Information about a strength reduction candidate. Each statement
62 in the candidate table represents an expression of one of the
63 following forms (the special case of CAND_REF will be described
64 later):
65
66 (CAND_MULT) S1: X = (B + i) * S
67 (CAND_ADD) S1: X = B + (i * S)
68
69 Here X and B are SSA names, i is an integer constant, and S is
70 either an SSA name or a constant. We call B the "base," i the
71 "index", and S the "stride."
72
73 Any statement S0 that dominates S1 and is of the form:
74
75 (CAND_MULT) S0: Y = (B + i') * S
76 (CAND_ADD) S0: Y = B + (i' * S)
77
78 is called a "basis" for S1. In both cases, S1 may be replaced by
79
80 S1': X = Y + (i - i') * S,
81
82 where (i - i') * S is folded to the extent possible.
83
84 All gimple statements are visited in dominator order, and each
85 statement that may contribute to one of the forms of S1 above is
86 given at least one entry in the candidate table. Such statements
87 include addition, pointer addition, subtraction, multiplication,
88 negation, copies, and nontrivial type casts. If a statement may
89 represent more than one expression of the forms of S1 above,
90 multiple "interpretations" are stored in the table and chained
91 together. Examples:
92
93 * An add of two SSA names may treat either operand as the base.
94 * A multiply of two SSA names, likewise.
95 * A copy or cast may be thought of as either a CAND_MULT with
96 i = 0 and S = 1, or as a CAND_ADD with i = 0 or S = 0.
97
98 Candidate records are allocated from an obstack. They are addressed
99 both from a hash table keyed on S1, and from a vector of candidate
100 pointers arranged in predominator order.
101
102 Opportunity note
103 ----------------
104 Currently we don't recognize:
105
106 S0: Y = (S * i') - B
107 S1: X = (S * i) - B
108
109 as a strength reduction opportunity, even though this S1 would
110 also be replaceable by the S1' above. This can be added if it
111 comes up in practice.
112
113 Strength reduction in addressing
114 --------------------------------
115 There is another kind of candidate known as CAND_REF. A CAND_REF
116 describes a statement containing a memory reference having
117 complex addressing that might benefit from strength reduction.
118 Specifically, we are interested in references for which
119 get_inner_reference returns a base address, offset, and bitpos as
120 follows:
121
122 base: MEM_REF (T1, C1)
123 offset: MULT_EXPR (PLUS_EXPR (T2, C2), C3)
124 bitpos: C4 * BITS_PER_UNIT
125
126 Here T1 and T2 are arbitrary trees, and C1, C2, C3, C4 are
127 arbitrary integer constants. Note that C2 may be zero, in which
128 case the offset will be MULT_EXPR (T2, C3).
129
130 When this pattern is recognized, the original memory reference
131 can be replaced with:
132
133 MEM_REF (POINTER_PLUS_EXPR (T1, MULT_EXPR (T2, C3)),
134 C1 + (C2 * C3) + C4)
135
136 which distributes the multiply to allow constant folding. When
137 two or more addressing expressions can be represented by MEM_REFs
138 of this form, differing only in the constants C1, C2, and C4,
139 making this substitution produces more efficient addressing during
140 the RTL phases. When there are not at least two expressions with
141 the same values of T1, T2, and C3, there is nothing to be gained
142 by the replacement.
143
144 Strength reduction of CAND_REFs uses the same infrastructure as
145 that used by CAND_MULTs and CAND_ADDs. We record T1 in the base (B)
146 field, MULT_EXPR (T2, C3) in the stride (S) field, and
147 C1 + (C2 * C3) + C4 in the index (i) field. A basis for a CAND_REF
148 is thus another CAND_REF with the same B and S values. When at
149 least two CAND_REFs are chained together using the basis relation,
150 each of them is replaced as above, resulting in improved code
151 generation for addressing.
152
153 Conditional candidates
154 ======================
155
156 Conditional candidates are best illustrated with an example.
157 Consider the code sequence:
158
159 (1) x_0 = ...;
160 (2) a_0 = x_0 * 5; MULT (B: x_0; i: 0; S: 5)
161 if (...)
162 (3) x_1 = x_0 + 1; ADD (B: x_0, i: 1; S: 1)
163 (4) x_2 = PHI <x_0, x_1>; PHI (B: x_0, i: 0, S: 1)
164 (5) x_3 = x_2 + 1; ADD (B: x_2, i: 1, S: 1)
165 (6) a_1 = x_3 * 5; MULT (B: x_2, i: 1; S: 5)
166
167 Here strength reduction is complicated by the uncertain value of x_2.
168 A legitimate transformation is:
169
170 (1) x_0 = ...;
171 (2) a_0 = x_0 * 5;
172 if (...)
173 {
174 (3) [x_1 = x_0 + 1;]
175 (3a) t_1 = a_0 + 5;
176 }
177 (4) [x_2 = PHI <x_0, x_1>;]
178 (4a) t_2 = PHI <a_0, t_1>;
179 (5) [x_3 = x_2 + 1;]
180 (6r) a_1 = t_2 + 5;
181
182 where the bracketed instructions may go dead.
183
184 To recognize this opportunity, we have to observe that statement (6)
185 has a "hidden basis" (2). The hidden basis is unlike a normal basis
186 in that the statement and the hidden basis have different base SSA
187 names (x_2 and x_0, respectively). The relationship is established
188 when a statement's base name (x_2) is defined by a phi statement (4),
189 each argument of which (x_0, x_1) has an identical "derived base name."
190 If the argument is defined by a candidate (as x_1 is by (3)) that is a
191 CAND_ADD having a stride of 1, the derived base name of the argument is
192 the base name of the candidate (x_0). Otherwise, the argument itself
193 is its derived base name (as is the case with argument x_0).
194
195 The hidden basis for statement (6) is the nearest dominating candidate
196 whose base name is the derived base name (x_0) of the feeding phi (4),
197 and whose stride is identical to that of the statement. We can then
198 create the new "phi basis" (4a) and feeding adds along incoming arcs (3a),
199 allowing the final replacement of (6) by the strength-reduced (6r).
200
201 To facilitate this, a new kind of candidate (CAND_PHI) is introduced.
202 A CAND_PHI is not a candidate for replacement, but is maintained in the
203 candidate table to ease discovery of hidden bases. Any phi statement
204 whose arguments share a common derived base name is entered into the
205 table with the derived base name, an (arbitrary) index of zero, and a
206 stride of 1. A statement with a hidden basis can then be detected by
207 simply looking up its feeding phi definition in the candidate table,
208 extracting the derived base name, and searching for a basis in the
209 usual manner after substituting the derived base name.
210
211 Note that the transformation is only valid when the original phi and
212 the statements that define the phi's arguments are all at the same
213 position in the loop hierarchy. */
214
215
216/* Index into the candidate vector, offset by 1. VECs are zero-based,
217 while cand_idx's are one-based, with zero indicating null. */
218typedef unsigned cand_idx;
219
220/* The kind of candidate. */
221enum cand_kind
222{
223 CAND_MULT,
224 CAND_ADD,
225 CAND_REF,
226 CAND_PHI
227};
228
229struct slsr_cand_d
230{
231 /* The candidate statement S1. */
232 gimple *cand_stmt;
233
234 /* The base expression B: often an SSA name, but not always. */
235 tree base_expr;
236
237 /* The stride S. */
238 tree stride;
239
240 /* The index constant i. */
241 widest_int index;
242
243 /* The type of the candidate. This is normally the type of base_expr,
244 but casts may have occurred when combining feeding instructions.
245 A candidate can only be a basis for candidates of the same final type.
246 (For CAND_REFs, this is the type to be used for operand 1 of the
247 replacement MEM_REF.) */
248 tree cand_type;
249
250 /* The type to be used to interpret the stride field when the stride
251 is not a constant. Normally the same as the type of the recorded
252 stride, but when the stride has been cast we need to maintain that
253 knowledge in order to make legal substitutions without losing
254 precision. When the stride is a constant, this will be sizetype. */
255 tree stride_type;
256
257 /* The kind of candidate (CAND_MULT, etc.). */
258 enum cand_kind kind;
259
260 /* Index of this candidate in the candidate vector. */
261 cand_idx cand_num;
262
263 /* Index of the next candidate record for the same statement.
264 A statement may be useful in more than one way (e.g., due to
265 commutativity). So we can have multiple "interpretations"
266 of a statement. */
267 cand_idx next_interp;
268
269 /* Index of the first candidate record in a chain for the same
270 statement. */
271 cand_idx first_interp;
272
273 /* Index of the basis statement S0, if any, in the candidate vector. */
274 cand_idx basis;
275
276 /* First candidate for which this candidate is a basis, if one exists. */
277 cand_idx dependent;
278
279 /* Next candidate having the same basis as this one. */
280 cand_idx sibling;
281
282 /* If this is a conditional candidate, the CAND_PHI candidate
283 that defines the base SSA name B. */
284 cand_idx def_phi;
285
286 /* Savings that can be expected from eliminating dead code if this
287 candidate is replaced. */
288 int dead_savings;
289};
290
291typedef struct slsr_cand_d slsr_cand, *slsr_cand_t;
292typedef const struct slsr_cand_d *const_slsr_cand_t;
293
294/* Pointers to candidates are chained together as part of a mapping
295 from base expressions to the candidates that use them. */
296
297struct cand_chain_d
298{
299 /* Base expression for the chain of candidates: often, but not
300 always, an SSA name. */
301 tree base_expr;
302
303 /* Pointer to a candidate. */
304 slsr_cand_t cand;
305
306 /* Chain pointer. */
307 struct cand_chain_d *next;
308
309};
310
311typedef struct cand_chain_d cand_chain, *cand_chain_t;
312typedef const struct cand_chain_d *const_cand_chain_t;
313
314/* Information about a unique "increment" associated with candidates
315 having an SSA name for a stride. An increment is the difference
316 between the index of the candidate and the index of its basis,
317 i.e., (i - i') as discussed in the module commentary.
318
319 When we are not going to generate address arithmetic we treat
320 increments that differ only in sign as the same, allowing sharing
321 of the cost of initializers. The absolute value of the increment
322 is stored in the incr_info. */
323
324struct incr_info_d
325{
326 /* The increment that relates a candidate to its basis. */
327 widest_int incr;
328
329 /* How many times the increment occurs in the candidate tree. */
330 unsigned count;
331
332 /* Cost of replacing candidates using this increment. Negative and
333 zero costs indicate replacement should be performed. */
334 int cost;
335
336 /* If this increment is profitable but is not -1, 0, or 1, it requires
337 an initializer T_0 = stride * incr to be found or introduced in the
338 nearest common dominator of all candidates. This field holds T_0
339 for subsequent use. */
340 tree initializer;
341
342 /* If the initializer was found to already exist, this is the block
343 where it was found. */
344 basic_block init_bb;
345};
346
347typedef struct incr_info_d incr_info, *incr_info_t;
348

404/* Produce a pointer to the IDX'th candidate in the candidate vector. */
405
406static slsr_cand_t
407lookup_cand (cand_idx idx)
408{
409 return cand_vec[idx - 1];

412/* Helper for hashing a candidate chain header. */
413
414struct cand_chain_hasher : nofree_ptr_hash <cand_chain>
415{
416 static inline hashval_t hash (const cand_chain *);
417 static inline bool equal (const cand_chain *, const cand_chain *);
418};
419
420inline hashval_t
421cand_chain_hasher::hash (const cand_chain *p)
422{
423 tree base_expr = p->base_expr;
424 return iterative_hash_expr (base_expr, 0);
425}
426
427inline bool
428cand_chain_hasher::equal (const cand_chain *chain1, const cand_chain *chain2)
429{
430 return operand_equal_p (chain1->base_expr, chain2->base_expr, 0);
431}

433/* Hash table embodying a mapping from base exprs to chains of candidates. */
434static hash_table<cand_chain_hasher> *base_cand_map;
435
436/* Pointer map used by tree_to_aff_combination_expand. */
437static hash_map<tree, name_expansion *> *name_expansions;
438/* Pointer map embodying a mapping from bases to alternative bases. */
439static hash_map<tree, tree> *alt_base_map;
440
441/* Given BASE, use the tree affine combiniation facilities to
442 find the underlying tree expression for BASE, with any
443 immediate offset excluded.
444
445 N.B. we should eliminate this backtracking with better forward
446 analysis in a future release. */
447
448static tree
449get_alternative_base (tree base)
450{
451 tree *result = alt_base_map->get (base);
452
453 if (result == NULL)
454 {
455 tree expr;
456 aff_tree aff;
457
458 tree_to_aff_combination_expand (base, TREE_TYPE (base),
459 &aff, &name_expansions);
460 aff.offset = 0;
461 expr = aff_combination_to_tree (&aff);
462
463 gcc_assert (!alt_base_map->put (base, base == expr ? NULL : expr));
464
465 return expr == base ? NULL : expr;
466 }
467
468 return *result;
469}
470
471/* Look in the candidate table for a CAND_PHI that defines BASE and
472 return it if found; otherwise return NULL. */
473
474static cand_idx
475find_phi_def (tree base)
476{
477 slsr_cand_t c;
478
479 if (TREE_CODE (base) != SSA_NAME)
480 return 0;
481
482 c = base_cand_from_table (base);
483
484 if (!c || c->kind != CAND_PHI
485 || SSA_NAME_OCCURS_IN_ABNORMAL_PHI (gimple_phi_result (c->cand_stmt)))
486 return 0;
487
488 return c->cand_num;
489}
490
491/* Helper routine for find_basis_for_candidate. May be called twice:
492 once for the candidate's base expr, and optionally again either for
493 the candidate's phi definition or for a CAND_REF's alternative base
494 expression. */
495
496static slsr_cand_t
497find_basis_for_base_expr (slsr_cand_t c, tree base_expr)
498{
499 cand_chain mapping_key;
500 cand_chain_t chain;
501 slsr_cand_t basis = NULL;
502
503 // Limit potential of N^2 behavior for long candidate chains.
504 int iters = 0;
505 int max_iters = PARAM_VALUE (PARAM_MAX_SLSR_CANDIDATE_SCAN);
506
507 mapping_key.base_expr = base_expr;
508 chain = base_cand_map->find (&mapping_key);
509
510 for (; chain && iters < max_iters; chain = chain->next, ++iters)
511 {
512 slsr_cand_t one_basis = chain->cand;
513
514 if (one_basis->kind != c->kind
515 || one_basis->cand_stmt == c->cand_stmt
516 || !operand_equal_p (one_basis->stride, c->stride, 0)
517 || !types_compatible_p (one_basis->cand_type, c->cand_type)
518 || !types_compatible_p (one_basis->stride_type, c->stride_type)
519 || !dominated_by_p (CDI_DOMINATORS,
520 gimple_bb (c->cand_stmt),
521 gimple_bb (one_basis->cand_stmt)))
522 continue;
523
524 tree lhs = gimple_assign_lhs (one_basis->cand_stmt);
525 if (lhs && TREE_CODE (lhs) == SSA_NAME
526 && SSA_NAME_OCCURS_IN_ABNORMAL_PHI (lhs))
527 continue;
528
529 if (!basis || basis->cand_num < one_basis->cand_num)
530 basis = one_basis;
531 }
532
533 return basis;
534}
535
536/* Use the base expr from candidate C to look for possible candidates
537 that can serve as a basis for C. Each potential basis must also
538 appear in a block that dominates the candidate statement and have
539 the same stride and type. If more than one possible basis exists,
540 the one with highest index in the vector is chosen; this will be
541 the most immediately dominating basis. */
542
543static int
544find_basis_for_candidate (slsr_cand_t c)
545{
546 slsr_cand_t basis = find_basis_for_base_expr (c, c->base_expr);
547
548 /* If a candidate doesn't have a basis using its base expression,
549 it may have a basis hidden by one or more intervening phis. */
550 if (!basis && c->def_phi)
551 {
552 basic_block basis_bb, phi_bb;
553 slsr_cand_t phi_cand = lookup_cand (c->def_phi);
554 basis = find_basis_for_base_expr (c, phi_cand->base_expr);
555
556 if (basis)
557 {
558 /* A hidden basis must dominate the phi-definition of the
559 candidate's base name. */
560 phi_bb = gimple_bb (phi_cand->cand_stmt);
561 basis_bb = gimple_bb (basis->cand_stmt);
562
563 if (phi_bb == basis_bb
564 || !dominated_by_p (CDI_DOMINATORS, phi_bb, basis_bb))
565 {
566 basis = NULL;
567 c->basis = 0;
568 }
569
570 /* If we found a hidden basis, estimate additional dead-code
571 savings if the phi and its feeding statements can be removed. */
572 if (basis && has_single_use (gimple_phi_result (phi_cand->cand_stmt)))
573 c->dead_savings += phi_cand->dead_savings;
574 }
575 }
576
577 if (flag_expensive_optimizations && !basis && c->kind == CAND_REF)
578 {
579 tree alt_base_expr = get_alternative_base (c->base_expr);
580 if (alt_base_expr)
581 basis = find_basis_for_base_expr (c, alt_base_expr);
582 }
583
584 if (basis)
585 {
586 c->sibling = basis->dependent;
587 basis->dependent = c->cand_num;
588 return basis->cand_num;
589 }
590
591 return 0;
592}
593
594/* Record a mapping from BASE to C, indicating that C may potentially serve
595 as a basis using that base expression. BASE may be the same as
596 C->BASE_EXPR; alternatively BASE can be a different tree that share the
597 underlining expression of C->BASE_EXPR. */
598
599static void
600record_potential_basis (slsr_cand_t c, tree base)
601{
602 cand_chain_t node;
603 cand_chain **slot;
604
605 gcc_assert (base);
606
607 node = (cand_chain_t) obstack_alloc (&chain_obstack, sizeof (cand_chain));
608 node->base_expr = base;
609 node->cand = c;
610 node->next = NULL;
611 slot = base_cand_map->find_slot (node, INSERT);
612
613 if (*slot)
614 {
615 cand_chain_t head = (cand_chain_t) (*slot);
616 node->next = head->next;
617 head->next = node;
618 }
619 else
620 *slot = node;
621}
622
623/* Allocate storage for a new candidate and initialize its fields.
624 Attempt to find a basis for the candidate.
625
626 For CAND_REF, an alternative base may also be recorded and used
627 to find a basis. This helps cases where the expression hidden
628 behind BASE (which is usually an SSA_NAME) has immediate offset,
629 e.g.
630
631 a2[i][j] = 1;
632 a2[i + 20][j] = 2; */
633
634static slsr_cand_t
635alloc_cand_and_find_basis (enum cand_kind kind, gimple *gs, tree base,
636 const widest_int &index, tree stride, tree ctype,
637 tree stype, unsigned savings)
638{
639 slsr_cand_t c = (slsr_cand_t) obstack_alloc (&cand_obstack,
640 sizeof (slsr_cand));
641 c->cand_stmt = gs;
642 c->base_expr = base;
643 c->stride = stride;
644 c->index = index;
645 c->cand_type = ctype;
646 c->stride_type = stype;
647 c->kind = kind;
648 c->cand_num = cand_vec.length () + 1;
649 c->next_interp = 0;
650 c->first_interp = c->cand_num;
651 c->dependent = 0;
652 c->sibling = 0;
653 c->def_phi = kind == CAND_MULT ? find_phi_def (base) : 0;
654 c->dead_savings = savings;
655
656 cand_vec.safe_push (c);
657
658 if (kind == CAND_PHI)
659 c->basis = 0;
660 else
661 c->basis = find_basis_for_candidate (c);
662
663 record_potential_basis (c, base);
664 if (flag_expensive_optimizations && kind == CAND_REF)
665 {
666 tree alt_base = get_alternative_base (base);
667 if (alt_base)
668 record_potential_basis (c, alt_base);
669 }
670
671 return c;
672}

674/* Determine the target cost of statement GS when compiling according
675 to SPEED. */
676
677static int
678stmt_cost (gimple *gs, bool speed)
679{
680 tree lhs, rhs1, rhs2;
681 machine_mode lhs_mode;
682
683 gcc_assert (is_gimple_assign (gs));
684 lhs = gimple_assign_lhs (gs);
685 rhs1 = gimple_assign_rhs1 (gs);
686 lhs_mode = TYPE_MODE (TREE_TYPE (lhs));
687
688 switch (gimple_assign_rhs_code (gs))
689 {
690 case MULT_EXPR:
691 rhs2 = gimple_assign_rhs2 (gs);
692
693 if (tree_fits_shwi_p (rhs2))
694 return mult_by_coeff_cost (tree_to_shwi (rhs2), lhs_mode, speed);
695
696 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (rhs1) != INTEGER_CST);
697 return mul_cost (speed, lhs_mode);
698
699 case PLUS_EXPR:
700 case POINTER_PLUS_EXPR:
701 case MINUS_EXPR:
702 return add_cost (speed, lhs_mode);
703
704 case NEGATE_EXPR:
705 return neg_cost (speed, lhs_mode);
706
707 CASE_CONVERT:
708 return convert_cost (lhs_mode, TYPE_MODE (TREE_TYPE (rhs1)), speed);
709
710 /* Note that we don't assign costs to copies that in most cases
711 will go away. */
712 case SSA_NAME:
713 return 0;
714
715 default:
716 ;
717 }
718
719 gcc_unreachable ();
720 return 0;
721}
722
723/* Look up the defining statement for BASE_IN and return a pointer
724 to its candidate in the candidate table, if any; otherwise NULL.
725 Only CAND_ADD and CAND_MULT candidates are returned. */
726
727static slsr_cand_t
728base_cand_from_table (tree base_in)
729{
730 slsr_cand_t *result;
731
732 gimple *def = SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (base_in);
733 if (!def)
734 return (slsr_cand_t) NULL;
735
736 result = stmt_cand_map->get (def);
737
738 if (result && (*result)->kind != CAND_REF)
739 return *result;
740
741 return (slsr_cand_t) NULL;
742}
743
744/* Add an entry to the statement-to-candidate mapping. */
745
746static void
747add_cand_for_stmt (gimple *gs, slsr_cand_t c)
748{
749 gcc_assert (!stmt_cand_map->put (gs, c));
750}

752/* Given PHI which contains a phi statement, determine whether it
753 satisfies all the requirements of a phi candidate. If so, create
754 a candidate. Note that a CAND_PHI never has a basis itself, but
755 is used to help find a basis for subsequent candidates. */
756
757static void
758slsr_process_phi (gphi *phi, bool speed)
759{
760 unsigned i;
761 tree arg0_base = NULL_TREE, base_type;
762 slsr_cand_t c;
763 struct loop *cand_loop = gimple_bb (phi)->loop_father;
764 unsigned savings = 0;
765
766 /* A CAND_PHI requires each of its arguments to have the same
767 derived base name. (See the module header commentary for a
768 definition of derived base names.) Furthermore, all feeding
769 definitions must be in the same position in the loop hierarchy
770 as PHI. */
771
772 for (i = 0; i < gimple_phi_num_args (phi); i++)
773 {
774 slsr_cand_t arg_cand;
775 tree arg = gimple_phi_arg_def (phi, i);
776 tree derived_base_name = NULL_TREE;
777 gimple *arg_stmt = NULL;
778 basic_block arg_bb = NULL;
779
780 if (TREE_CODE (arg) != SSA_NAME)
781 return;
782
783 arg_cand = base_cand_from_table (arg);
784
785 if (arg_cand)
786 {
787 while (arg_cand->kind != CAND_ADD && arg_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
788 {
789 if (!arg_cand->next_interp)
790 return;
791
792 arg_cand = lookup_cand (arg_cand->next_interp);
793 }
794
795 if (!integer_onep (arg_cand->stride))
796 return;
797
798 derived_base_name = arg_cand->base_expr;
799 arg_stmt = arg_cand->cand_stmt;
800 arg_bb = gimple_bb (arg_stmt);
801
802 /* Gather potential dead code savings if the phi statement
803 can be removed later on. */
804 if (has_single_use (arg))
805 {
806 if (gimple_code (arg_stmt) == GIMPLE_PHI)
807 savings += arg_cand->dead_savings;
808 else
809 savings += stmt_cost (arg_stmt, speed);
810 }
811 }
812 else if (SSA_NAME_IS_DEFAULT_DEF (arg))
813 {
814 derived_base_name = arg;
815 arg_bb = single_succ (ENTRY_BLOCK_PTR_FOR_FN (cfun));
816 }
817
818 if (!arg_bb || arg_bb->loop_father != cand_loop)
819 return;
820
821 if (i == 0)
822 arg0_base = derived_base_name;
823 else if (!operand_equal_p (derived_base_name, arg0_base, 0))
824 return;
825 }
826
827 /* Create the candidate. "alloc_cand_and_find_basis" is named
828 misleadingly for this case, as no basis will be sought for a
829 CAND_PHI. */
830 base_type = TREE_TYPE (arg0_base);
831
832 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_PHI, phi, arg0_base,
833 0, integer_one_node, base_type,
834 sizetype, savings);
835
836 /* Add the candidate to the statement-candidate mapping. */
837 add_cand_for_stmt (phi, c);
838}
839
840/* Given PBASE which is a pointer to tree, look up the defining
841 statement for it and check whether the candidate is in the
842 form of:
843
844 X = B + (1 * S), S is integer constant
845 X = B + (i * S), S is integer one
846
847 If so, set PBASE to the candidate's base_expr and return double
848 int (i * S).
849 Otherwise, just return double int zero. */
850
851static widest_int
852backtrace_base_for_ref (tree *pbase)
853{
854 tree base_in = *pbase;
855 slsr_cand_t base_cand;
856
857 STRIP_NOPS (base_in);
858
859 /* Strip off widening conversion(s) to handle cases where
860 e.g. 'B' is widened from an 'int' in order to calculate
861 a 64-bit address. */
862 if (CONVERT_EXPR_P (base_in)
863 && legal_cast_p_1 (TREE_TYPE (base_in),
864 TREE_TYPE (TREE_OPERAND (base_in, 0))))
865 base_in = get_unwidened (base_in, NULL_TREE);
866
867 if (TREE_CODE (base_in) != SSA_NAME)
868 return 0;
869
870 base_cand = base_cand_from_table (base_in);
871
872 while (base_cand && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
873 {
874 if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD
875 && base_cand->index == 1
876 && TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
877 {
878 /* X = B + (1 * S), S is integer constant. */
879 *pbase = base_cand->base_expr;
880 return wi::to_widest (base_cand->stride);
881 }
882 else if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD
883 && TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST
884 && integer_onep (base_cand->stride))
885 {
886 /* X = B + (i * S), S is integer one. */
887 *pbase = base_cand->base_expr;
888 return base_cand->index;
889 }
890
891 if (base_cand->next_interp)
892 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
893 else
894 base_cand = NULL;
895 }
896
897 return 0;
898}
899
900/* Look for the following pattern:
901
902 *PBASE: MEM_REF (T1, C1)
903
904 *POFFSET: MULT_EXPR (T2, C3) [C2 is zero]
905 or
906 MULT_EXPR (PLUS_EXPR (T2, C2), C3)
907 or
908 MULT_EXPR (MINUS_EXPR (T2, -C2), C3)
909
910 *PINDEX: C4 * BITS_PER_UNIT
911
912 If not present, leave the input values unchanged and return FALSE.
913 Otherwise, modify the input values as follows and return TRUE:
914
915 *PBASE: T1
916 *POFFSET: MULT_EXPR (T2, C3)
917 *PINDEX: C1 + (C2 * C3) + C4
918
919 When T2 is recorded by a CAND_ADD in the form of (T2' + C5), it
920 will be further restructured to:
921
922 *PBASE: T1
923 *POFFSET: MULT_EXPR (T2', C3)
924 *PINDEX: C1 + (C2 * C3) + C4 + (C5 * C3) */
925
926static bool
927restructure_reference (tree *pbase, tree *poffset, widest_int *pindex,
928 tree *ptype)
929{
930 tree base = *pbase, offset = *poffset;
931 widest_int index = *pindex;
932 tree mult_op0, t1, t2, type;
933 widest_int c1, c2, c3, c4, c5;
934
935 if (!base
936 || !offset
937 || TREE_CODE (base) != MEM_REF
938 || TREE_CODE (offset) != MULT_EXPR
939 || TREE_CODE (TREE_OPERAND (offset, 1)) != INTEGER_CST
940 || wi::umod_floor (index, BITS_PER_UNIT) != 0)
941 return false;
942
943 t1 = TREE_OPERAND (base, 0);
944 c1 = widest_int::from (mem_ref_offset (base), SIGNED);
945 type = TREE_TYPE (TREE_OPERAND (base, 1));
946
947 mult_op0 = TREE_OPERAND (offset, 0);
948 c3 = wi::to_widest (TREE_OPERAND (offset, 1));
949
950 if (TREE_CODE (mult_op0) == PLUS_EXPR)
951
952 if (TREE_CODE (TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 1)) == INTEGER_CST)
953 {
954 t2 = TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 0);
955 c2 = wi::to_widest (TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 1));
956 }
957 else
958 return false;
959
960 else if (TREE_CODE (mult_op0) == MINUS_EXPR)
961
962 if (TREE_CODE (TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 1)) == INTEGER_CST)
963 {
964 t2 = TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 0);
965 c2 = -wi::to_widest (TREE_OPERAND (mult_op0, 1));
966 }
967 else
968 return false;
969
970 else
971 {
972 t2 = mult_op0;
973 c2 = 0;
974 }
975
976 c4 = index >> LOG2_BITS_PER_UNIT;
977 c5 = backtrace_base_for_ref (&t2);
978
979 *pbase = t1;
980 *poffset = fold_build2 (MULT_EXPR, sizetype, fold_convert (sizetype, t2),
981 wide_int_to_tree (sizetype, c3));
982 *pindex = c1 + c2 * c3 + c4 + c5 * c3;
983 *ptype = type;
984
985 return true;
986}
987
988/* Given GS which contains a data reference, create a CAND_REF entry in
989 the candidate table and attempt to find a basis. */
990
991static void
992slsr_process_ref (gimple *gs)
993{
994 tree ref_expr, base, offset, type;
995 HOST_WIDE_INT bitsize, bitpos;
996 machine_mode mode;
997 int unsignedp, reversep, volatilep;
998 slsr_cand_t c;
999
1000 if (gimple_vdef (gs))
1001 ref_expr = gimple_assign_lhs (gs);
1002 else
1003 ref_expr = gimple_assign_rhs1 (gs);
1004
1005 if (!handled_component_p (ref_expr)
1006 || TREE_CODE (ref_expr) == BIT_FIELD_REF
1007 || (TREE_CODE (ref_expr) == COMPONENT_REF
1008 && DECL_BIT_FIELD (TREE_OPERAND (ref_expr, 1))))
1009 return;
1010
1011 base = get_inner_reference (ref_expr, &bitsize, &bitpos, &offset, &mode,
1012 &unsignedp, &reversep, &volatilep);
1013 if (reversep)
1014 return;
1015 widest_int index = bitpos;
1016
1017 if (!restructure_reference (&base, &offset, &index, &type))
1018 return;
1019
1020 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_REF, gs, base, index, offset,
1021 type, sizetype, 0);
1022
1023 /* Add the candidate to the statement-candidate mapping. */
1024 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1025}

1027/* Create a candidate entry for a statement GS, where GS multiplies
1028 two SSA names BASE_IN and STRIDE_IN. Propagate any known information
1029 about the two SSA names into the new candidate. Return the new
1030 candidate. */
1031
1032static slsr_cand_t
1033create_mul_ssa_cand (gimple *gs, tree base_in, tree stride_in, bool speed)
1034{
1035 tree base = NULL_TREE, stride = NULL_TREE, ctype = NULL_TREE;
1036 tree stype = NULL_TREE;
1037 widest_int index;
1038 unsigned savings = 0;
1039 slsr_cand_t c;
1040 slsr_cand_t base_cand = base_cand_from_table (base_in);
1041
1042 /* Look at all interpretations of the base candidate, if necessary,
1043 to find information to propagate into this candidate. */
1044 while (base_cand && !base && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1045 {
1046
1047 if (base_cand->kind == CAND_MULT && integer_onep (base_cand->stride))
1048 {
1049 /* Y = (B + i') * 1
1050 X = Y * Z
1051 ================
1052 X = (B + i') * Z */
1053 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1054 index = base_cand->index;
1055 stride = stride_in;
1056 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1057 stype = TREE_TYPE (stride_in);
1058 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1059 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1060 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1061 }
1062 else if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD
1063 && TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
1064 {
1065 /* Y = B + (i' * S), S constant
1066 X = Y * Z
1067 ============================
1068 X = B + ((i' * S) * Z) */
1069 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1070 index = base_cand->index * wi::to_widest (base_cand->stride);
1071 stride = stride_in;
1072 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1073 stype = TREE_TYPE (stride_in);
1074 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1075 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1076 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1077 }
1078
1079 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1080 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1081 else
1082 base_cand = NULL;
1083 }
1084
1085 if (!base)
1086 {
1087 /* No interpretations had anything useful to propagate, so
1088 produce X = (Y + 0) * Z. */
1089 base = base_in;
1090 index = 0;
1091 stride = stride_in;
1092 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1093 stype = TREE_TYPE (stride_in);
1094 }
1095
1096 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_MULT, gs, base, index, stride,
1097 ctype, stype, savings);
1098 return c;
1099}

1101/* Create a candidate entry for a statement GS, where GS multiplies
1102 SSA name BASE_IN by constant STRIDE_IN. Propagate any known
1103 information about BASE_IN into the new candidate. Return the new
1104 candidate. */
1105
1106static slsr_cand_t
1107create_mul_imm_cand (gimple *gs, tree base_in, tree stride_in, bool speed)
1108{
1109 tree base = NULL_TREE, stride = NULL_TREE, ctype = NULL_TREE;
1110 widest_int index, temp;
1111 unsigned savings = 0;
1112 slsr_cand_t c;
1113 slsr_cand_t base_cand = base_cand_from_table (base_in);
1114
1115 /* Look at all interpretations of the base candidate, if necessary,
1116 to find information to propagate into this candidate. */
1117 while (base_cand && !base && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1118 {
1119 if (base_cand->kind == CAND_MULT
1120 && TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
1121 {
1122 /* Y = (B + i') * S, S constant
1123 X = Y * c
1124 ============================
1125 X = (B + i') * (S * c) */
1126 temp = wi::to_widest (base_cand->stride) * wi::to_widest (stride_in);
1127 if (wi::fits_to_tree_p (temp, TREE_TYPE (stride_in)))
1128 {
1129 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1130 index = base_cand->index;
1131 stride = wide_int_to_tree (TREE_TYPE (stride_in), temp);
1132 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1133 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1134 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1135 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1136 }
1137 }
1138 else if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD && integer_onep (base_cand->stride))
1139 {
1140 /* Y = B + (i' * 1)
1141 X = Y * c
1142 ===========================
1143 X = (B + i') * c */
1144 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1145 index = base_cand->index;
1146 stride = stride_in;
1147 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1148 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1149 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1150 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1151 }
1152 else if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD
1153 && base_cand->index == 1
1154 && TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
1155 {
1156 /* Y = B + (1 * S), S constant
1157 X = Y * c
1158 ===========================
1159 X = (B + S) * c */
1160 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1161 index = wi::to_widest (base_cand->stride);
1162 stride = stride_in;
1163 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1164 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1165 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1166 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1167 }
1168
1169 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1170 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1171 else
1172 base_cand = NULL;
1173 }
1174
1175 if (!base)
1176 {
1177 /* No interpretations had anything useful to propagate, so
1178 produce X = (Y + 0) * c. */
1179 base = base_in;
1180 index = 0;
1181 stride = stride_in;
1182 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1183 }
1184
1185 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_MULT, gs, base, index, stride,
1186 ctype, sizetype, savings);
1187 return c;
1188}
1189
1190/* Given GS which is a multiply of scalar integers, make an appropriate
1191 entry in the candidate table. If this is a multiply of two SSA names,
1192 create two CAND_MULT interpretations and attempt to find a basis for
1193 each of them. Otherwise, create a single CAND_MULT and attempt to
1194 find a basis. */
1195
1196static void
1197slsr_process_mul (gimple *gs, tree rhs1, tree rhs2, bool speed)
1198{
1199 slsr_cand_t c, c2;
1200
1201 /* If this is a multiply of an SSA name with itself, it is highly
1202 unlikely that we will get a strength reduction opportunity, so
1203 don't record it as a candidate. This simplifies the logic for
1204 finding a basis, so if this is removed that must be considered. */
1205 if (rhs1 == rhs2)
1206 return;
1207
1208 if (TREE_CODE (rhs2) == SSA_NAME)
1209 {
1210 /* Record an interpretation of this statement in the candidate table
1211 assuming RHS1 is the base expression and RHS2 is the stride. */
1212 c = create_mul_ssa_cand (gs, rhs1, rhs2, speed);
1213
1214 /* Add the first interpretation to the statement-candidate mapping. */
1215 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1216
1217 /* Record another interpretation of this statement assuming RHS1
1218 is the stride and RHS2 is the base expression. */
1219 c2 = create_mul_ssa_cand (gs, rhs2, rhs1, speed);
1220 c->next_interp = c2->cand_num;
1221 c2->first_interp = c->cand_num;
1222 }
1223 else
1224 {
1225 /* Record an interpretation for the multiply-immediate. */
1226 c = create_mul_imm_cand (gs, rhs1, rhs2, speed);
1227
1228 /* Add the interpretation to the statement-candidate mapping. */
1229 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1230 }
1231}
1232
1233/* Create a candidate entry for a statement GS, where GS adds two
1234 SSA names BASE_IN and ADDEND_IN if SUBTRACT_P is false, and
1235 subtracts ADDEND_IN from BASE_IN otherwise. Propagate any known
1236 information about the two SSA names into the new candidate.
1237 Return the new candidate. */
1238
1239static slsr_cand_t
1240create_add_ssa_cand (gimple *gs, tree base_in, tree addend_in,
1241 bool subtract_p, bool speed)
1242{
1243 tree base = NULL_TREE, stride = NULL_TREE, ctype = NULL_TREE;
1244 tree stype = NULL_TREE;
1245 widest_int index;
1246 unsigned savings = 0;
1247 slsr_cand_t c;
1248 slsr_cand_t base_cand = base_cand_from_table (base_in);
1249 slsr_cand_t addend_cand = base_cand_from_table (addend_in);
1250
1251 /* The most useful transformation is a multiply-immediate feeding
1252 an add or subtract. Look for that first. */
1253 while (addend_cand && !base && addend_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1254 {
1255 if (addend_cand->kind == CAND_MULT
1256 && addend_cand->index == 0
1257 && TREE_CODE (addend_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
1258 {
1259 /* Z = (B + 0) * S, S constant
1260 X = Y +/- Z
1261 ===========================
1262 X = Y + ((+/-1 * S) * B) */
1263 base = base_in;
1264 index = wi::to_widest (addend_cand->stride);
1265 if (subtract_p)
1266 index = -index;
1267 stride = addend_cand->base_expr;
1268 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1269 stype = addend_cand->cand_type;
1270 if (has_single_use (addend_in))
1271 savings = (addend_cand->dead_savings
1272 + stmt_cost (addend_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1273 }
1274
1275 if (addend_cand->next_interp)
1276 addend_cand = lookup_cand (addend_cand->next_interp);
1277 else
1278 addend_cand = NULL;
1279 }
1280
1281 while (base_cand && !base && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1282 {
1283 if (base_cand->kind == CAND_ADD
1284 && (base_cand->index == 0
1285 || operand_equal_p (base_cand->stride,
1286 integer_zero_node, 0)))
1287 {
1288 /* Y = B + (i' * S), i' * S = 0
1289 X = Y +/- Z
1290 ============================
1291 X = B + (+/-1 * Z) */
1292 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1293 index = subtract_p ? -1 : 1;
1294 stride = addend_in;
1295 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1296 stype = (TREE_CODE (addend_in) == INTEGER_CST ? sizetype
1297 : TREE_TYPE (addend_in));
1298 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1299 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1300 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1301 }
1302 else if (subtract_p)
1303 {
1304 slsr_cand_t subtrahend_cand = base_cand_from_table (addend_in);
1305
1306 while (subtrahend_cand && !base && subtrahend_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1307 {
1308 if (subtrahend_cand->kind == CAND_MULT
1309 && subtrahend_cand->index == 0
1310 && TREE_CODE (subtrahend_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST)
1311 {
1312 /* Z = (B + 0) * S, S constant
1313 X = Y - Z
1314 ===========================
1315 Value: X = Y + ((-1 * S) * B) */
1316 base = base_in;
1317 index = wi::to_widest (subtrahend_cand->stride);
1318 index = -index;
1319 stride = subtrahend_cand->base_expr;
1320 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1321 stype = subtrahend_cand->cand_type;
1322 if (has_single_use (addend_in))
1323 savings = (subtrahend_cand->dead_savings
1324 + stmt_cost (subtrahend_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1325 }
1326
1327 if (subtrahend_cand->next_interp)
1328 subtrahend_cand = lookup_cand (subtrahend_cand->next_interp);
1329 else
1330 subtrahend_cand = NULL;
1331 }
1332 }
1333
1334 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1335 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1336 else
1337 base_cand = NULL;
1338 }
1339
1340 if (!base)
1341 {
1342 /* No interpretations had anything useful to propagate, so
1343 produce X = Y + (1 * Z). */
1344 base = base_in;
1345 index = subtract_p ? -1 : 1;
1346 stride = addend_in;
1347 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1348 stype = (TREE_CODE (addend_in) == INTEGER_CST ? sizetype
1349 : TREE_TYPE (addend_in));
1350 }
1351
1352 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_ADD, gs, base, index, stride,
1353 ctype, stype, savings);
1354 return c;
1355}
1356
1357/* Create a candidate entry for a statement GS, where GS adds SSA
1358 name BASE_IN to constant INDEX_IN. Propagate any known information
1359 about BASE_IN into the new candidate. Return the new candidate. */
1360
1361static slsr_cand_t
1362create_add_imm_cand (gimple *gs, tree base_in, const widest_int &index_in,
1363 bool speed)
1364{
1365 enum cand_kind kind = CAND_ADD;
1366 tree base = NULL_TREE, stride = NULL_TREE, ctype = NULL_TREE;
1367 tree stype = NULL_TREE;
1368 widest_int index, multiple;
1369 unsigned savings = 0;
1370 slsr_cand_t c;
1371 slsr_cand_t base_cand = base_cand_from_table (base_in);
1372
1373 while (base_cand && !base && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1374 {
1375 signop sign = TYPE_SIGN (TREE_TYPE (base_cand->stride));
1376
1377 if (TREE_CODE (base_cand->stride) == INTEGER_CST
1378 && wi::multiple_of_p (index_in, wi::to_widest (base_cand->stride),
1379 sign, &multiple))
1380 {
1381 /* Y = (B + i') * S, S constant, c = kS for some integer k
1382 X = Y + c
1383 ============================
1384 X = (B + (i'+ k)) * S
1385 OR
1386 Y = B + (i' * S), S constant, c = kS for some integer k
1387 X = Y + c
1388 ============================
1389 X = (B + (i'+ k)) * S */
1390 kind = base_cand->kind;
1391 base = base_cand->base_expr;
1392 index = base_cand->index + multiple;
1393 stride = base_cand->stride;
1394 ctype = base_cand->cand_type;
1395 stype = base_cand->stride_type;
1396 if (has_single_use (base_in))
1397 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1398 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1399 }
1400
1401 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1402 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1403 else
1404 base_cand = NULL;
1405 }
1406
1407 if (!base)
1408 {
1409 /* No interpretations had anything useful to propagate, so
1410 produce X = Y + (c * 1). */
1411 kind = CAND_ADD;
1412 base = base_in;
1413 index = index_in;
1414 stride = integer_one_node;
1415 ctype = TREE_TYPE (base_in);
1416 stype = sizetype;
1417 }
1418
1419 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (kind, gs, base, index, stride,
1420 ctype, stype, savings);
1421 return c;
1422}
1423
1424/* Given GS which is an add or subtract of scalar integers or pointers,
1425 make at least one appropriate entry in the candidate table. */
1426
1427static void
1428slsr_process_add (gimple *gs, tree rhs1, tree rhs2, bool speed)
1429{
1430 bool subtract_p = gimple_assign_rhs_code (gs) == MINUS_EXPR;
1431 slsr_cand_t c = NULL, c2;
1432
1433 if (TREE_CODE (rhs2) == SSA_NAME)
1434 {
1435 /* First record an interpretation assuming RHS1 is the base expression
1436 and RHS2 is the stride. But it doesn't make sense for the
1437 stride to be a pointer, so don't record a candidate in that case. */
1438 if (!POINTER_TYPE_P (TREE_TYPE (rhs2)))
1439 {
1440 c = create_add_ssa_cand (gs, rhs1, rhs2, subtract_p, speed);
1441
1442 /* Add the first interpretation to the statement-candidate
1443 mapping. */
1444 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1445 }
1446
1447 /* If the two RHS operands are identical, or this is a subtract,
1448 we're done. */
1449 if (operand_equal_p (rhs1, rhs2, 0) || subtract_p)
1450 return;
1451
1452 /* Otherwise, record another interpretation assuming RHS2 is the
1453 base expression and RHS1 is the stride, again provided that the
1454 stride is not a pointer. */
1455 if (!POINTER_TYPE_P (TREE_TYPE (rhs1)))
1456 {
1457 c2 = create_add_ssa_cand (gs, rhs2, rhs1, false, speed);
1458 if (c)
1459 {
1460 c->next_interp = c2->cand_num;
1461 c2->first_interp = c->cand_num;
1462 }
1463 else
1464 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c2);
1465 }
1466 }
1467 else
1468 {
1469 /* Record an interpretation for the add-immediate. */
1470 widest_int index = wi::to_widest (rhs2);
1471 if (subtract_p)
1472 index = -index;
1473
1474 c = create_add_imm_cand (gs, rhs1, index, speed);
1475
1476 /* Add the interpretation to the statement-candidate mapping. */
1477 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1478 }
1479}
1480
1481/* Given GS which is a negate of a scalar integer, make an appropriate
1482 entry in the candidate table. A negate is equivalent to a multiply
1483 by -1. */
1484
1485static void
1486slsr_process_neg (gimple *gs, tree rhs1, bool speed)
1487{
1488 /* Record a CAND_MULT interpretation for the multiply by -1. */
1489 slsr_cand_t c = create_mul_imm_cand (gs, rhs1, integer_minus_one_node, speed);
1490
1491 /* Add the interpretation to the statement-candidate mapping. */
1492 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1493}
1494
1495/* Help function for legal_cast_p, operating on two trees. Checks
1496 whether it's allowable to cast from RHS to LHS. See legal_cast_p
1497 for more details. */
1498
1499static bool
1500legal_cast_p_1 (tree lhs_type, tree rhs_type)
1501{
1502 unsigned lhs_size, rhs_size;
1503 bool lhs_wraps, rhs_wraps;
1504
1505 lhs_size = TYPE_PRECISION (lhs_type);
1506 rhs_size = TYPE_PRECISION (rhs_type);
1507 lhs_wraps = ANY_INTEGRAL_TYPE_P (lhs_type) && TYPE_OVERFLOW_WRAPS (lhs_type);
1508 rhs_wraps = ANY_INTEGRAL_TYPE_P (rhs_type) && TYPE_OVERFLOW_WRAPS (rhs_type);
1509
1510 if (lhs_size < rhs_size
1511 || (rhs_wraps && !lhs_wraps)
1512 || (rhs_wraps && lhs_wraps && rhs_size != lhs_size))
1513 return false;
1514
1515 return true;
1516}
1517
1518/* Return TRUE if GS is a statement that defines an SSA name from
1519 a conversion and is legal for us to combine with an add and multiply
1520 in the candidate table. For example, suppose we have:
1521
1522 A = B + i;
1523 C = (type) A;
1524 D = C * S;
1525
1526 Without the type-cast, we would create a CAND_MULT for D with base B,
1527 index i, and stride S. We want to record this candidate only if it
1528 is equivalent to apply the type cast following the multiply:
1529
1530 A = B + i;
1531 E = A * S;
1532 D = (type) E;
1533
1534 We will record the type with the candidate for D. This allows us
1535 to use a similar previous candidate as a basis. If we have earlier seen
1536
1537 A' = B + i';
1538 C' = (type) A';
1539 D' = C' * S;
1540
1541 we can replace D with
1542
1543 D = D' + (i - i') * S;
1544
1545 But if moving the type-cast would change semantics, we mustn't do this.
1546
1547 This is legitimate for casts from a non-wrapping integral type to
1548 any integral type of the same or larger size. It is not legitimate
1549 to convert a wrapping type to a non-wrapping type, or to a wrapping
1550 type of a different size. I.e., with a wrapping type, we must
1551 assume that the addition B + i could wrap, in which case performing
1552 the multiply before or after one of the "illegal" type casts will
1553 have different semantics. */
1554
1555static bool
1556legal_cast_p (gimple *gs, tree rhs)
1557{
1558 if (!is_gimple_assign (gs)
1559 || !CONVERT_EXPR_CODE_P (gimple_assign_rhs_code (gs)))
1560 return false;
1561
1562 return legal_cast_p_1 (TREE_TYPE (gimple_assign_lhs (gs)), TREE_TYPE (rhs));
1563}
1564
1565/* Given GS which is a cast to a scalar integer type, determine whether
1566 the cast is legal for strength reduction. If so, make at least one
1567 appropriate entry in the candidate table. */
1568
1569static void
1570slsr_process_cast (gimple *gs, tree rhs1, bool speed)
1571{
1572 tree lhs, ctype;
1573 slsr_cand_t base_cand, c = NULL, c2;
1574 unsigned savings = 0;
1575
1576 if (!legal_cast_p (gs, rhs1))
1577 return;
1578
1579 lhs = gimple_assign_lhs (gs);
1580 base_cand = base_cand_from_table (rhs1);
1581 ctype = TREE_TYPE (lhs);
1582
1583 if (base_cand && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1584 {
1585 slsr_cand_t first_cand = NULL;
1586
1587 while (base_cand)
1588 {
1589 /* Propagate all data from the base candidate except the type,
1590 which comes from the cast, and the base candidate's cast,
1591 which is no longer applicable. */
1592 if (has_single_use (rhs1))
1593 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1594 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1595
1596 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (base_cand->kind, gs,
1597 base_cand->base_expr,
1598 base_cand->index, base_cand->stride,
1599 ctype, base_cand->stride_type,
1600 savings);
1601 if (!first_cand)
1602 first_cand = c;
1603
1604 if (first_cand != c)
1605 c->first_interp = first_cand->cand_num;
1606
1607 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1608 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1609 else
1610 base_cand = NULL;
1611 }
1612 }
1613 else
1614 {
1615 /* If nothing is known about the RHS, create fresh CAND_ADD and
1616 CAND_MULT interpretations:
1617
1618 X = Y + (0 * 1)
1619 X = (Y + 0) * 1
1620
1621 The first of these is somewhat arbitrary, but the choice of
1622 1 for the stride simplifies the logic for propagating casts
1623 into their uses. */
1624 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_ADD, gs, rhs1, 0,
1625 integer_one_node, ctype, sizetype, 0);
1626 c2 = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_MULT, gs, rhs1, 0,
1627 integer_one_node, ctype, sizetype, 0);
1628 c->next_interp = c2->cand_num;
1629 c2->first_interp = c->cand_num;
1630 }
1631
1632 /* Add the first (or only) interpretation to the statement-candidate
1633 mapping. */
1634 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1635}
1636
1637/* Given GS which is a copy of a scalar integer type, make at least one
1638 appropriate entry in the candidate table.
1639
1640 This interface is included for completeness, but is unnecessary
1641 if this pass immediately follows a pass that performs copy
1642 propagation, such as DOM. */
1643
1644static void
1645slsr_process_copy (gimple *gs, tree rhs1, bool speed)
1646{
1647 slsr_cand_t base_cand, c = NULL, c2;
1648 unsigned savings = 0;
1649
1650 base_cand = base_cand_from_table (rhs1);
1651
1652 if (base_cand && base_cand->kind != CAND_PHI)
1653 {
1654 slsr_cand_t first_cand = NULL;
1655
1656 while (base_cand)
1657 {
1658 /* Propagate all data from the base candidate. */
1659 if (has_single_use (rhs1))
1660 savings = (base_cand->dead_savings
1661 + stmt_cost (base_cand->cand_stmt, speed));
1662
1663 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (base_cand->kind, gs,
1664 base_cand->base_expr,
1665 base_cand->index, base_cand->stride,
1666 base_cand->cand_type,
1667 base_cand->stride_type, savings);
1668 if (!first_cand)
1669 first_cand = c;
1670
1671 if (first_cand != c)
1672 c->first_interp = first_cand->cand_num;
1673
1674 if (base_cand->next_interp)
1675 base_cand = lookup_cand (base_cand->next_interp);
1676 else
1677 base_cand = NULL;
1678 }
1679 }
1680 else
1681 {
1682 /* If nothing is known about the RHS, create fresh CAND_ADD and
1683 CAND_MULT interpretations:
1684
1685 X = Y + (0 * 1)
1686 X = (Y + 0) * 1
1687
1688 The first of these is somewhat arbitrary, but the choice of
1689 1 for the stride simplifies the logic for propagating casts
1690 into their uses. */
1691 c = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_ADD, gs, rhs1, 0,
1692 integer_one_node, TREE_TYPE (rhs1),
1693 sizetype, 0);
1694 c2 = alloc_cand_and_find_basis (CAND_MULT, gs, rhs1, 0,
1695 integer_one_node, TREE_TYPE (rhs1),
1696 sizetype, 0);
1697 c->next_interp = c2->cand_num;
1698 c2->first_interp = c->cand_num;
1699 }
1700
1701 /* Add the first (or only) interpretation to the statement-candidate
1702 mapping. */
1703 add_cand_for_stmt (gs, c);
1704}
1705
1706class find_candidates_dom_walker : public dom_walker
1707{
1708public:
1709 find_candidates_dom_walker (cdi_direction direction)
1710 : dom_walker (direction) {}
1711 virtual edge before_dom_children (basic_block);
1712};
1713
1714/* Find strength-reduction candidates in block BB. */
1715
1716edge
1717find_candidates_dom_walker::before_dom_children (basic_block bb)
1718{
1719 bool speed = optimize_bb_for_speed_p (bb);
1720
1721 for (gphi_iterator gsi = gsi_start_phis (bb); !gsi_end_p (gsi);
1722 gsi_next (&gsi))
1723 slsr_process_phi (gsi.phi (), speed);
1724
1725 for (gimple_stmt_iterator gsi = gsi_start_bb (bb); !gsi_end_p (gsi);
1726 gsi_next (&gsi))
1727 {
1728 gimple *gs = gsi_stmt (gsi);
1729
1730 if (stmt_could_throw_p (gs))
1731 continue;
1732
1733 if (gimple_vuse (gs) && gimple_assign_single_p (gs))
1734 slsr_process_ref (gs);
1735
1736 else if (is_gimple_assign (gs)
1737 && SCALAR_INT_MODE_P
1738 (TYPE_MODE (TREE_TYPE (gimple_assign_lhs (gs)))))
1739 {
1740 tree rhs1 = NULL_TREE, rhs2 = NULL_TREE;
1741
1742 switch (gimple_assign_rhs_code (gs))
1743 {
1744 case MULT_EXPR:
1745 case PLUS_EXPR:
1746 rhs1 = gimple_assign_rhs1 (gs);
1747 rhs2 = gimple_assign_rhs2 (gs);
1748 /* Should never happen, but currently some buggy situations
1749 in earlier phases put constants in rhs1. */
1750 if (TREE_CODE (rhs1) != SSA_NAME)
1751 continue;
1752 break;
1753
1754 /* Possible future opportunity: rhs1 of a ptr+ can be
1755 an ADDR_EXPR. */
1756 case POINTER_PLUS_EXPR:
1757 case MINUS_EXPR:
1758 rhs2 = gimple_assign_rhs2 (gs);
1759 gcc_fallthrough ();
1760
1761 CASE_CONVERT:
1762 case SSA_NAME:
1763 case NEGATE_EXPR:
1764 rhs1 = gimple_assign_rhs1 (gs);
1765 if (TREE_CODE (rhs1) != SSA_NAME)
1766 continue;
1767 break;
1768
1769 default:
1770 ;
1771 }
1772
1773 switch (gimple_assign_rhs_code (gs))
1774 {
1775 case MULT_EXPR:
1776 slsr_process_mul (gs, rhs1, rhs2, speed);
1777 break;
1778
1779 case PLUS_EXPR:
1780 case POINTER_PLUS_EXPR:
1781 case MINUS_EXPR:
1782 slsr_process_add (gs, rhs1, rhs2, speed);
1783 break;
1784
1785 case NEGATE_EXPR:
1786 slsr_process_neg (gs, rhs1, speed);
1787 break;
1788
1789 CASE_CONVERT:
1790 slsr_process_cast (gs, rhs1, speed);
1791 break;
1792
1793 case SSA_NAME:
1794 slsr_process_copy (gs, rhs1, speed);
1795 break;
1796
1797 default:
1798 ;
1799 }
1800 }
1801 }
1802 return NULL;
1803}

1805/* Dump a candidate for debug. */
1806
1807static void
1808dump_candidate (slsr_cand_t c)
1809{
1810 fprintf (dump_file, "%3d [%d] ", c->cand_num,
1811 gimple_bb (c->cand_stmt)->index);
1812 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, c->cand_stmt, 0, 0);
1813 switch (c->kind)
1814 {
1815 case CAND_MULT:
1816 fputs (" MULT : (", dump_file);
1817 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->base_expr, 0);
1818 fputs (" + ", dump_file);
1819 print_decs (c->index, dump_file);
1820 fputs (") * ", dump_file);
1821 if (TREE_CODE (c->stride) != INTEGER_CST
1822 && c->stride_type != TREE_TYPE (c->stride))
1823 {
1824 fputs ("(", dump_file);
1825 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride_type, 0);
1826 fputs (")", dump_file);
1827 }
1828 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride, 0);
1829 fputs (" : ", dump_file);
1830 break;
1831 case CAND_ADD:
1832 fputs (" ADD : ", dump_file);
1833 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->base_expr, 0);
1834 fputs (" + (", dump_file);
1835 print_decs (c->index, dump_file);
1836 fputs (" * ", dump_file);
1837 if (TREE_CODE (c->stride) != INTEGER_CST
1838 && c->stride_type != TREE_TYPE (c->stride))
1839 {
1840 fputs ("(", dump_file);
1841 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride_type, 0);
1842 fputs (")", dump_file);
1843 }
1844 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride, 0);
1845 fputs (") : ", dump_file);
1846 break;
1847 case CAND_REF:
1848 fputs (" REF : ", dump_file);
1849 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->base_expr, 0);
1850 fputs (" + (", dump_file);
1851 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride, 0);
1852 fputs (") + ", dump_file);
1853 print_decs (c->index, dump_file);
1854 fputs (" : ", dump_file);
1855 break;
1856 case CAND_PHI:
1857 fputs (" PHI : ", dump_file);
1858 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->base_expr, 0);
1859 fputs (" + (unknown * ", dump_file);
1860 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->stride, 0);
1861 fputs (") : ", dump_file);
1862 break;
1863 default:
1864 gcc_unreachable ();
1865 }
1866 print_generic_expr (dump_file, c->cand_type, 0);
1867 fprintf (dump_file, "\n basis: %d dependent: %d sibling: %d\n",
1868 c->basis, c->dependent, c->sibling);
1869 fprintf (dump_file,
1870 " next-interp: %d first-interp: %d dead-savings: %d\n",
1871 c->next_interp, c->first_interp, c->dead_savings);
1872 if (c->def_phi)
1873 fprintf (dump_file, " phi: %d\n", c->def_phi);
1874 fputs ("\n", dump_file);
1875}

1943
1944/* Replace *EXPR in candidate C with an equivalent strength-reduced
1945 data reference. */
1946
1947static void
1948replace_ref (tree *expr, slsr_cand_t c)
1949{
1950 tree add_expr, mem_ref, acc_type = TREE_TYPE (*expr);
1951 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT misalign;
1952 unsigned align;
1953
1954 /* Ensure the memory reference carries the minimum alignment
1955 requirement for the data type. See PR58041. */
1956 get_object_alignment_1 (*expr, &align, &misalign);
1957 if (misalign != 0)
1958 align = least_bit_hwi (misalign);
1959 if (align < TYPE_ALIGN (acc_type))
1960 acc_type = build_aligned_type (acc_type, align);
1961
1962 add_expr = fold_build2 (POINTER_PLUS_EXPR, c->cand_type,
1963 c->base_expr, c->stride);
1964 mem_ref = fold_build2 (MEM_REF, acc_type, add_expr,
1965 wide_int_to_tree (c->cand_type, c->index));
1966
1967 /* Gimplify the base addressing expression for the new MEM_REF tree. */
1968 gimple_stmt_iterator gsi = gsi_for_stmt (c->cand_stmt);
1969 TREE_OPERAND (mem_ref, 0)
1970 = force_gimple_operand_gsi (&gsi, TREE_OPERAND (mem_ref, 0),
1971 /*simple_p=*/true, NULL,
1972 /*before=*/true, GSI_SAME_STMT);
1973 copy_ref_info (mem_ref, *expr);
1974 *expr = mem_ref;
1975 update_stmt (c->cand_stmt);
1976}
1977
1978/* Replace CAND_REF candidate C, each sibling of candidate C, and each
1979 dependent of candidate C with an equivalent strength-reduced data
1980 reference. */
1981
1982static void
1983replace_refs (slsr_cand_t c)
1984{
1985 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1986 {
1987 fputs ("Replacing reference: ", dump_file);
1988 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, c->cand_stmt, 0, 0);
1989 }
1990
1991 if (gimple_vdef (c->cand_stmt))
1992 {
1993 tree *lhs = gimple_assign_lhs_ptr (c->cand_stmt);
1994 replace_ref (lhs, c);
1995 }
1996 else
1997 {
1998 tree *rhs = gimple_assign_rhs1_ptr (c->cand_stmt);
1999 replace_ref (rhs, c);
2000 }
2001
2002 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2003 {
2004 fputs ("With: ", dump_file);
2005 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, c->cand_stmt, 0, 0);
2006 fputs ("\n", dump_file);
2007 }
2008
2009 if (c->sibling)
2010 replace_refs (lookup_cand (c->sibling));
2011
2012 if (c->dependent)
2013 replace_refs (lookup_cand (c->dependent));
2014}
2015
2016/* Return TRUE if candidate C is dependent upon a PHI. */
2017
2018static bool
2019phi_dependent_cand_p (slsr_cand_t c)
2020{
2021 /* A candidate is not necessarily dependent upon a PHI just because
2022 it has a phi definition for its base name. It may have a basis
2023 that relies upon the same phi definition, in which case the PHI
2024 is irrelevant to this candidate. */
2025 return (c->def_phi
2026 && c->basis
2027 && lookup_cand (c->basis)->def_phi != c->def_phi);
2028}
2029
2030/* Calculate the increment required for candidate C relative to
2031 its basis. */
2032
2033static widest_int
2034cand_increment (slsr_cand_t c)
2035{
2036 slsr_cand_t basis;
2037
2038 /* If the candidate doesn't have a basis, just return its own
2039 index. This is useful in record_increments to help us find
2040 an existing initializer. Also, if the candidate's basis is
2041 hidden by a phi, then its own index will be the increment
2042 from the newly introduced phi basis. */
2043 if (!c->basis || phi_dependent_cand_p (c))
2044 return c->index;
2045
2046 basis = lookup_cand (c->basis);
2047 gcc_assert (operand_equal_p (c->base_expr, basis->base_expr, 0));
2048 return c->index - basis->index;
2049}
2050
2051/* Calculate the increment required for candidate C relative to
2052 its basis. If we aren't going to generate pointer arithmetic
2053 for this candidate, return the absolute value of that increment
2054 instead. */
2055
2056static inline widest_int
2057cand_abs_increment (slsr_cand_t c)
2058{
2059 widest_int increment = cand_increment (c);
2060
2061 if (!address_arithmetic_p && wi::neg_p (increment))
2062 increment = -increment;
2063
2064 return increment;
2065}
2066
2067/* Return TRUE iff candidate C has already been replaced under
2068 another interpretation. */
2069
2070static inline bool
2071cand_already_replaced (slsr_cand_t c)
2072{
2073 return (gimple_bb (c->cand_stmt) == 0);
2074}
2075
2076/* Common logic used by replace_unconditional_candidate and
2077 replace_conditional_candidate. */
2078
2079static void
2080replace_mult_candidate (slsr_cand_t c, tree basis_name, widest_int bump)
2081{
2082 tree target_type = TREE_TYPE (gimple_assign_lhs (c->cand_stmt));
2083 enum tree_code cand_code = gimple_assign_rhs_code (c->cand_stmt);
2084
2085 /* It is not useful to replace casts, copies, negates, or adds of
2086 an SSA name and a constant. */
2087 if (cand_code == SSA_NAME
2088 || CONVERT_EXPR_CODE_P (cand_code)
2089 || cand_code == PLUS_EXPR
2090 || cand_code == POINTER_PLUS_EXPR
2091 || cand_code == MINUS_EXPR
2092 || cand_code == NEGATE_EXPR)
2093 return;
2094
2095 enum tree_code code = PLUS_EXPR;
2096 tree bump_tree;
2097 gimple *stmt_to_print = NULL;
2098
2099 /* If the basis name and the candidate's LHS have incompatible
2100 types, introduce a cast. */
2101 if (!useless_type_conversion_p (target_type, TREE_TYPE (basis_name)))
2102 basis_name = introduce_cast_before_cand (c, target_type, basis_name);
2103 if (wi::neg_p (bump))
2104 {
2105 code = MINUS_EXPR;
2106 bump = -bump;
2107 }
2108
2109 /* It is possible that the resulting bump doesn't fit in target_type.
2110 Abandon the replacement in this case. This does not affect
2111 siblings or dependents of C. */
2112 if (bump != wi::ext (bump, TYPE_PRECISION (target_type),
2113 TYPE_SIGN (target_type)))
2114 return;
2115
2116 bump_tree = wide_int_to_tree (target_type, bump);
2117
2118 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2119 {
2120 fputs ("Replacing: ", dump_file);
2121 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, c->cand_stmt, 0, 0);
2122 }
2123
2124 if (bump == 0)
2125 {
2126 tree lhs = gimple_assign_lhs (c->cand_stmt);
2127 gassign *copy_stmt = gimple_build_assign (lhs, basis_name);
2128 gimple_stmt_iterator gsi = gsi_for_stmt (c->cand_stmt);
2129 slsr_cand_t cc = lookup_cand (c->first_interp);
2130 gimple_set_location (copy_stmt, gimple_location (c->cand_stmt));
2131 gsi_replace (&gsi, copy_stmt, false);
2132 while (cc)
2133 {
2134 cc->cand_stmt = copy_stmt;
2135 cc = cc->next_interp ? lookup_cand (cc->next_interp) : NULL;
2136 }
2137 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2138 stmt_to_print = copy_stmt;
2139 }
2140 else
2141 {
2142 tree rhs1, rhs2;
2143 if (cand_code != NEGATE_EXPR) {
2144 rhs1 = gimple_assign_rhs1 (c->cand_stmt);
2145 rhs2 = gimple_assign_rhs2 (c->cand_stmt);
2146 }
2147 if (cand_code != NEGATE_EXPR
2148 && ((operand_equal_p (rhs1, basis_name, 0)
2149 && operand_equal_p (rhs2, bump_tree, 0))
2150 || (operand_equal_p (rhs1, bump_tree, 0)
2151 && operand_equal_p (rhs2, basis_name, 0))))
2152 {
2153 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2154 {
2155 fputs ("(duplicate, not actually replacing)", dump_file);
2156 stmt_to_print = c->cand_stmt;
2157 }
2158 }
2159 else
2160 {
2161 gimple_stmt_iterator gsi = gsi_for_stmt (c->cand_stmt);
2162 slsr_cand_t cc = lookup_cand (c->first_interp);
2163 gimple_assign_set_rhs_with_ops (&gsi, code,
2164 basis_name, bump_tree);
2165 update_stmt (gsi_stmt (gsi));
2166 while (cc)
2167 {
2168 cc->cand_stmt = gsi_stmt (gsi);
2169 cc = cc->next_interp ? lookup_cand (cc->next_interp) : NULL;
2170 }
2171 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2172 stmt_to_print = gsi_stmt (gsi);
2173 }
2174 }
2175
2176 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2177 {
2178 fputs ("With: ", dump_file);
2179 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, stmt_to_print, 0, 0);
2180 fputs ("\n", dump_file);
2181 }
2182}
2183
2184/* Replace candidate C with an add or subtract. Note that we only
2185 operate on CAND_MULTs with known strides, so we will never generate
2186 a POINTER_PLUS_EXPR. Each candidate X = (B + i) * S is replaced by
2187 X = Y + ((i - i') * S), as described in the module commentary. The
2188 folded value ((i - i') * S) is referred to here as the "bump." */
2189
2190static void
2191replace_unconditional_candidate (slsr_cand_t c)
2192{
2193 slsr_cand_t basis;
2194
2195 if (cand_already_replaced (c))
2196 return;
2197
2198 basis = lookup_cand (c->basis);
2199 widest_int bump = cand_increment (c) * wi::to_widest (c->stride);
2200
2201 replace_mult_candidate (c, gimple_assign_lhs (basis->cand_stmt), bump);
2202}
2203
2204/* Return the index in the increment vector of the given INCREMENT,
2205 or -1 if not found. The latter can occur if more than
2206 MAX_INCR_VEC_LEN increments have been found. */
2207
2208static inline int
2209incr_vec_index (const widest_int &increment)
2210{
2211 unsigned i;
2212
2213 for (i = 0; i < incr_vec_len && increment != incr_vec[i].incr; i++)
2214 ;
2215
2216 if (i < incr_vec_len)
2217 return i;
2218 else
2219 return -1;
2220}
2221
2222/* Create a new statement along edge E to add BASIS_NAME to the product
2223 of INCREMENT and the stride of candidate C. Create and return a new
2224 SSA name from *VAR to be used as the LHS of the new statement.
2225 KNOWN_STRIDE is true iff C's stride is a constant. */
2226
2227static tree
2228create_add_on_incoming_edge (slsr_cand_t c, tree basis_name,
2229 widest_int increment, edge e, location_t loc,
2230 bool known_stride)
2231{
2232 tree lhs, basis_type;
2233 gassign *new_stmt, *cast_stmt = NULL;
2234
2235 /* If the add candidate along this incoming edge has the same
2236 index as C's hidden basis, the hidden basis represents this
2237 edge correctly. */
2238 if (increment == 0)
2239 return basis_name;
2240
2241 basis_type = TREE_TYPE (basis_name);
2242 lhs = make_temp_ssa_name (basis_type, NULL, "slsr");
2243
2244 /* Occasionally people convert integers to pointers without a
2245 cast, leading us into trouble if we aren't careful. */
2246 enum tree_code plus_code
2247 = POINTER_TYPE_P (basis_type) ? POINTER_PLUS_EXPR : PLUS_EXPR;
2248
2249 if (known_stride)
2250 {
2251 tree bump_tree;
2252 enum tree_code code = plus_code;
2253 widest_int bump = increment * wi::to_widest (c->stride);
2254 if (wi::neg_p (bump) && !POINTER_TYPE_P (basis_type))
2255 {
2256 code = MINUS_EXPR;
2257 bump = -bump;
2258 }
2259
2260 tree stride_type = POINTER_TYPE_P (basis_type) ? sizetype : basis_type;
2261 bump_tree = wide_int_to_tree (stride_type, bump);
2262 new_stmt = gimple_build_assign (lhs, code, basis_name, bump_tree);
2263 }
2264 else
2265 {
2266 int i;
2267 bool negate_incr = !POINTER_TYPE_P (basis_type) && wi::neg_p (increment);
2268 i = incr_vec_index (negate_incr ? -increment : increment);
2269 gcc_assert (i >= 0);
2270
2271 if (incr_vec[i].initializer)
2272 {
2273 enum tree_code code = negate_incr ? MINUS_EXPR : plus_code;
2274 new_stmt = gimple_build_assign (lhs, code, basis_name,
2275 incr_vec[i].initializer);
2276 }
2277 else {
2278 tree stride;
2279
2280 if (!types_compatible_p (TREE_TYPE (c->stride), c->stride_type))
2281 {
2282 tree cast_stride = make_temp_ssa_name (c->stride_type, NULL,
2283 "slsr");
2284 cast_stmt = gimple_build_assign (cast_stride, NOP_EXPR,
2285 c->stride);
2286 stride = cast_stride;
2287 }
2288 else
2289 stride = c->stride;
2290
2291 if (increment == 1)
2292 new_stmt = gimple_build_assign (lhs, plus_code, basis_name, stride);
2293 else if (increment == -1)
2294 new_stmt = gimple_build_assign (lhs, MINUS_EXPR, basis_name, stride);
2295 else
2296 gcc_unreachable ();
2297 }
2298 }
2299
2300 if (cast_stmt)
2301 {
2302 gimple_set_location (cast_stmt, loc);
2303 gsi_insert_on_edge (e, cast_stmt);
2304 }
2305
2306 gimple_set_location (new_stmt, loc);
2307 gsi_insert_on_edge (e, new_stmt);
2308
2309 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2310 {
2311 if (cast_stmt)
2312 {
2313 fprintf (dump_file, "Inserting cast on edge %d->%d: ",
2314 e->src->index, e->dest->index);
2315 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, cast_stmt, 0, 0);
2316 }
2317 fprintf (dump_file, "Inserting on edge %d->%d: ", e->src->index,
2318 e->dest->index);
2319 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, new_stmt, 0, 0);
2320 }
2321
2322 return lhs;
2323}
2324
2325/* Given a candidate C with BASIS_NAME being the LHS of C's basis which
2326 is hidden by the phi node FROM_PHI, create a new phi node in the same
2327 block as FROM_PHI. The new phi is suitable for use as a basis by C,
2328 with its phi arguments representing conditional adjustments to the
2329 hidden basis along conditional incoming paths. Those adjustments are
2330 made by creating add statements (and sometimes recursively creating
2331 phis) along those incoming paths. LOC is the location to attach to
2332 the introduced statements. KNOWN_STRIDE is true iff C's stride is a
2333 constant. */
2334
2335static tree
2336create_phi_basis (slsr_cand_t c, gimple *from_phi, tree basis_name,
2337 location_t loc, bool known_stride)
2338{
2339 int i;
2340 tree name, phi_arg;
2341 gphi *phi;
2342 slsr_cand_t basis = lookup_cand (c->basis);
2343 int nargs = gimple_phi_num_args (from_phi);
2344 basic_block phi_bb = gimple_bb (from_phi);
2345 slsr_cand_t phi_cand = *stmt_cand_map->get (from_phi);
2346 auto_vec<tree> phi_args (nargs);
2347
2348 /* Process each argument of the existing phi that represents
2349 conditionally-executed add candidates. */
2350 for (i = 0; i < nargs; i++)
2351 {
2352 edge e = (*phi_bb->preds)[i];
2353 tree arg = gimple_phi_arg_def (from_phi, i);
2354 tree feeding_def;
2355
2356 /* If the phi argument is the base name of the CAND_PHI, then
2357 this incoming arc should use the hidden basis. */
2358 if (operand_equal_p (arg, phi_cand->base_expr, 0))
2359 if (basis->index == 0)
2360 feeding_def = gimple_assign_lhs (basis->cand_stmt);
2361 else
2362 {
2363 widest_int incr = -basis->index;
2364 feeding_def = create_add_on_incoming_edge (c, basis_name, incr,
2365 e, loc, known_stride);
2366 }
2367 else
2368 {
2369 gimple *arg_def = SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (arg);
2370
2371 /* If there is another phi along this incoming edge, we must
2372 process it in the same fashion to ensure that all basis
2373 adjustments are made along its incoming edges. */
2374 if (gimple_code (arg_def) == GIMPLE_PHI)
2375 feeding_def = create_phi_basis (c, arg_def, basis_name,
2376 loc, known_stride);
2377 else
2378 {
2379 slsr_cand_t arg_cand = base_cand_from_table (arg);
2380 widest_int diff = arg_cand->index - basis->index;
2381 feeding_def = create_add_on_incoming_edge (c, basis_name, diff,
2382 e, loc, known_stride);
2383 }
2384 }
2385
2386 /* Because of recursion, we need to save the arguments in a vector
2387 so we can create the PHI statement all at once. Otherwise the
2388 storage for the half-created PHI can be reclaimed. */
2389 phi_args.safe_push (feeding_def);
2390 }
2391
2392 /* Create the new phi basis. */
2393 name = make_temp_ssa_name (TREE_TYPE (basis_name), NULL, "slsr");
2394 phi = create_phi_node (name, phi_bb);
2395 SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (name) = phi;
2396
2397 FOR_EACH_VEC_ELT (phi_args, i, phi_arg)
2398 {
2399 edge e = (*phi_bb->preds)[i];
2400 add_phi_arg (phi, phi_arg, e, loc);
2401 }
2402
2403 update_stmt (phi);
2404
2405 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2406 {
2407 fputs ("Introducing new phi basis: ", dump_file);
2408 print_gimple_stmt (dump_file, phi, 0, 0);
2409 }
2410
2411 return name;
2412}
2413
2414/* Given a candidate C whose basis is hidden by at least one intervening
2415 phi, introduce a matching number of new phis to represent its basis
2416 adjusted by conditional increments along possible incoming paths. Then
2417 replace C as though it were an unconditional candidate, using the new
2418 basis. */
2419
2420static void
2421replace_conditional_candidate (slsr_cand_t c)
2422{
2423 tree basis_name, name;
2424 slsr_cand_t basis;
2425 location_t loc;
2426
2427 /* Look up the LHS SSA name from C's basis. This will be the
2428 RHS1 of the adds we will introduce to create new phi arguments. */
2429 basis = lookup_cand (c->basis);
2430 basis_name = gimple_assign_lhs (basis->cand_stmt);
2431
2432 /* Create a new phi statement which will represent C's true basis
2433 after the transformation is complete. */
2434 loc = gimple_location (c->cand_stmt);
2435 name = create_phi_basis (c, lookup_cand (c->def_phi)->cand_stmt,
2436 basis_name, loc, KNOWN_STRIDE);
2437 /* Replace C with an add of the new basis phi and a constant. */
2438 widest_int bump = c->index * wi::to_widest (c->stride);
2439
2440 replace_mult_candidate (c, name, bump);
2441}
2442
2443/* Compute the expected costs of inserting basis adjustments for
2444 candidate C with phi-definition PHI. The cost of inserting
2445 one adjustment is given by ONE_ADD_COST. If PHI has arguments
2446 which are themselves phi results, recursively calculate costs
2447 for those phis as well. */
2448
2449static int
2450phi_add_costs (gimple *phi, slsr_cand_t c, int one_add_cost)
2451{
2452 unsigned i;
2453 int cost = 0;
2454 slsr_cand_t phi_cand = *stmt_cand_map->get (phi);
2455
2456 /* If we work our way back to a phi that isn't dominated by the hidden
2457 basis, this isn't a candidate for replacement. Indicate this by
2458 returning an unreasonably high cost. It's not easy to detect
2459 these situations when determining the basis, so we defer the
2460 decision until now. */
2461 basic_block phi_bb = gimple_bb (phi);
2462 slsr_cand_t basis = lookup_cand (c->basis);
2463 basic_block basis_bb = gimple_bb (basis->cand_stmt);
2464
2465 if (phi_bb == basis_bb || !dominated_by_p (CDI_DOMINATORS, phi_bb, basis_bb))
2466 return COST_INFINITE;
2467
2468 for (i = 0; i < gimple_phi_num_args (phi); i++)
2469 {
2470 tree arg = gimple_phi_arg_def (phi, i);
2471
2472 if (arg != phi_cand->base_expr)
2473 {
2474 gimple *arg_def = SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (arg);
2475
2476 if (gimple_code (arg_def) == GIMPLE_PHI)
2477 cost += phi_add_costs (arg_def, c, one_add_cost);
2478 else
2479 {
2480 slsr_cand_t arg_cand = base_cand_from_table (arg);
2481
2482 if (arg_cand->index != c->index)
2483 cost += one_add_cost;
2484 }
2485 }
2486 }
2487
2488 return cost;
2489}
2490
2491/* For candidate C, each sibling of candidate C, and each dependent of
2492 candidate C, determine whether the candidate is dependent upon a
2493 phi that hides its basis. If not, replace the candidate unconditionally.
2494 Otherwise, determine whether the cost of introducing compensation code
2495 for the candidate is offset by the gains from strength reduction. If
2496 so, replace the candidate and introduce the compensation code. */
2497
2498static void
2499replace_uncond_cands_and_profitable_phis (slsr_cand_t c)
2500{
2501 if (phi_dependent_cand_p (c))
2502 {
2503 if (c->kind == CAND_MULT)
2504 {
2505 /* A candidate dependent upon a phi will replace a multiply by
2506 a constant with an add, and will insert at most one add for
2507 each phi argument. Add these costs with the potential dead-code
2508 savings to determine profitability. */
2509 bool speed = optimize_bb_for_speed_p (gimple_bb (c->cand_stmt));
2510 int mult_savings = stmt_cost (c->cand_stmt, speed);
2511 gimple *phi = lookup_cand (c->def_phi)->cand_stmt;
2512 tree phi_result = gimple_phi_result (phi);
2513 int one_add_cost = add_cost (speed,
2514 TYPE_MODE (TREE_TYPE (phi_result)));
2515 int add_costs = one_add_cost + phi_add_costs (phi, c, one_add_cost);
2516 int cost = add_costs - mult_savings - c->dead_savings;
2517
2518 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2519 {
2520 fprintf (dump_file, " Conditional candidate %d:\n", c->cand_num);
2521 fprintf (dump_file, " add_costs = %d\n", add_costs);
2522 fprintf (dump_file, " mult_savings = %d\n", mult_savings);
2523 fprintf (dump_file, " dead_savings = %d\n", c->dead_savings);
2524 fprintf (dump_file, " cost = %d\n", cost);
2525 if (cost <= COST_NEUTRAL)
2526 fputs (" Replacing...\n", dump_file);
2527 else
2528 fputs (" Not replaced.\n", dump_file);
2529 }
2530
2531 if (cost <= COST_NEUTRAL)
2532 replace_conditional_candidate (c);
2533 }
2534 }
2535 else
2536 replace_unconditional_candidate (c);
2537
2538 if (c->sibling)
2539 replace_uncond_cands_and_profitable_phis (lookup_cand (c->sibling));
2540
2541 if (c->dependent)
2542 replace_uncond_cands_and_profitable_phis (lookup_cand (c->dependent));
2543}
2544
2545/* Count the number of candidates in the tree rooted at C that have
2546 not already been replaced under other interpretations. */
2547
2548static int
2549count_candidates (slsr_cand_t c)
2550{
2551 unsigned count = cand_already_replaced (c) ? 0 : 1;
2552
2553 if (c->sibling)
2554 count += count_candidates (lookup_cand (c->sibling));
2555
2556 if (c->dependent)
2557 count += count_candidates (lookup_cand (c->dependent));
2558
2559 return count;
2560}
2561
2562/* Increase the count of INCREMENT by one in the increment vector.
2563 INCREMENT is associated with candidate C. If INCREMENT is to be
2564 conditionally executed as part of a conditional candidate replacement,
2565 IS_PHI_ADJUST is true, otherwise false. If an initializer
2566 T_0 = stride * I is provided by a candidate that dominates all
2567 candidates with the same increment, also record T_0 for subsequent use. */
2568
2569static void
2570record_increment (slsr_cand_t c, widest_int increment, bool is_phi_adjust)
2571{
2572 bool found = false;
2573 unsigned i;
2574
2575 /* Treat increments that differ only in sign as identical so as to
2576 share initializers, unless we are generating pointer arithmetic. */
2577 if (!address_arithmetic_p && wi::neg_p (increment))
2578 increment = -increment;
2579
2580 for (i = 0; i < incr_vec_len; i++)
2581 {
2582 if (incr_vec[i].incr == increment)
2583 {
2584 incr_vec[i].count++;
2585 found = true;
2586
2587 /* If we previously recorded an initializer that doesn't
2588 dominate this candidate, it's not going to be useful to
2589 us after all. */
2590 if (incr_vec[i].initializer
2591 && !dominated_by_p (CDI_DOMINATORS,
2592 gimple_bb (c->cand_stmt),
2593 incr_vec[i].init_bb))
2594 {
2595 incr_vec[i].initializer = NULL_TREE;
2596 incr_vec[i].init_bb = NULL;
2597 }
2598
2599 break;
2600 }
2601 }
2602
2603 if (!found && incr_vec_len < MAX_INCR_VEC_LEN - 1)
2604 {
2605 /* The first time we see an increment, create the entry for it.
2606 If this is the root candidate which doesn't have a basis, set
2607 the count to zero. We're only processing it so it can possibly
2608 provide an initializer for other candidates. */
2609 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].incr = increment;
2610 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].count = c->basis || is_phi_adjust ? 1 : 0;
2611 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].cost = COST_INFINITE;
2612
2613 /* Optimistically record the first occurrence of this increment
2614 as providing an initializer (if it does); we will revise this
2615 opinion later if it doesn't dominate all other occurrences.
2616 Exception: increments of 0, 1 never need initializers;
2617 and phi adjustments don't ever provide initializers. */
2618 if (c->kind == CAND_ADD
2619 && !is_phi_adjust
2620 && c->index == increment
2621 && (increment > 1 || increment < 0)
2622 && (gimple_assign_rhs_code (c->cand_stmt) == PLUS_EXPR
2623 || gimple_assign_rhs_code (c->cand_stmt) == POINTER_PLUS_EXPR))
2624 {
2625 tree t0 = NULL_TREE;
2626 tree rhs1 = gimple_assign_rhs1 (c->cand_stmt);
2627 tree rhs2 = gimple_assign_rhs2 (c->cand_stmt);
2628 if (operand_equal_p (rhs1, c->base_expr, 0))
2629 t0 = rhs2;
2630 else if (operand_equal_p (rhs2, c->base_expr, 0))
2631 t0 = rhs1;
2632 if (t0
2633 && SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (t0)
2634 && gimple_bb (SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (t0)))
2635 {
2636 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].initializer = t0;
2637 incr_vec[incr_vec_len++].init_bb
2638 = gimple_bb (SSA_NAME_DEF_STMT (t0));
2639 }
2640 else
2641 {
2642 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].initializer = NULL_TREE;
2643 incr_vec[incr_vec_len++].init_bb = NULL;
2644 }
2645 }
2646 else
2647 {
2648 incr_vec[incr_vec_len].initializer = NULL_TREE;
2649 incr_vec[incr_vec_len++].init_bb = NULL;
2650 }
2651 }
2652}
